(4) Limits
==========

Limits of Functions \[4.1\]
---------------------------

Intuitively limits of functions are the expected value of a function at
points that can’t be solved because they are undefined, e.g.\
 \
[\$\\frac{(x-2)\\left( x+2 \\right)}{\\left( x-2 \\right)}\$]{.math
.inline} would be undefined at x=2, however as x is made sufficiently
close to 2, that value will become arbitrarily close to 4.

### The Limit Generally

From early calculus the limit of [*f*(*x*)]{.math .inline}, as
[*x*]{.math .inline} approaches [*a*]{.math .inline} was said to be some
value L, denoted [lim~*x* → *a*~(*f*(*x*)) = *L*]{.math .inline}\
\
[\$\$\\begin{aligned} \\forall \\varepsilon &gt; 0, \\enspace, \\exists
\\delta: & \\notag \\\\ & \\qquad 0 &lt; \\lvert x-a \\rvert &lt;
\\delta \\implies \\lvert f\\left( x \\right) - L \\rvert &lt;
\\varepsilon \\label{stewartlimdef}\\end{aligned}\$\$]{.math .display}\

##### Remarks on this Definition

Observe that the following statements are equivalent:

1.  [\$x\\neq c \\enspace \\wedge \\enspace \\lvert x-a \\rvert &lt;
    \\delta\$]{.math .inline}

2.  [0 &lt; |*x* − *a*|&lt;*δ*]{.math .inline}

3.  [|*x* − *a*|∈(0,*δ*)]{.math .inline}

##### Notation

 \
 \
If [*L*]{.math .inline} is a limit of [*f*]{.math .inline} at
[*c*]{.math .inline}, then it is said that:

1.  [*f*]{.math .inline} converges to [*L*]{.math .inline} at
    [*c*]{.math .inline}

2.  [*f*(*x*)]{.math .inline} approaches [*L*]{.math .inline} as
    [*x*]{.math .inline} approaches [*c*]{.math .inline} This is
    sometimes expressed with the symbolism [*f*(*x*) → *L*]{.math
    .inline} as [*x* → *c*]{.math .inline}

 \
And the following notation is used

1.  [lim~*x* → *c*~(*f*(*x*)) = *L*]{.math .inline}

2.  [lim~*x* → *c*~*f*]{.math .inline}

### The Limit Using Cluster Points

In analysis we more or less use the same definition but we introduce the
concept of cluster points to make it more rigorous.

##### Neighborhoods \[2.2.7\]

A neighborhood is an interval about a value, e.g. the [*ε*]{.math
.inline}-neighborhood of [*a*]{.math .inline} is some set
[*V*~*ε*~(*a*)]{.math .inline}:\
[\$\$\\begin{aligned} V\_{\\varepsilon}(a) = \\left( \\varepsilon-a,
\\varepsilon+a \\right) &= \\left\\{ x : \\varepsilon - a &lt; x &lt;
\\varepsilon + a \\right\\} \\\\ &= \\left\\{ x : -\\varepsilon &lt; x -
a &lt; \\varepsilon \\right\\} \\\\ &= \\left\\{ x: \\lvert x-a \\rvert
&lt; \\varepsilon \\right\\} \\label{nebhdef}\\end{aligned}\$\$]{.math
.display}\

##### Cluster Points

Let [*c*]{.math .inline} be a real number and let [*A*]{.math .inline}
be a subset of the real numbers, [*c*]{.math .inline} may or may not be
contained by [*A*]{.math .inline} it doesn’t matter.\
Take some interval around [*c*]{.math .inline}, or rather consider the
[*ε*]{.math .inline}-neighborhood of [*c*]{.math .inline},\
if, some value (other than [*c*]{.math .inline}) can be found inside
that interval/neighborhood that is also inside [*A*]{.math .inline},
regardless of how small that interval is made, Then [*c*]{.math .inline}
is said to be a cluster point of [*A*]{.math .inline}.\
 \
i.e., if the following is true\
[\$\\forall \\varepsilon &gt; 0, \\enspace \\exists x\\neq c \\in A\\cap
V\_{\\varepsilon}(c)\$]{.math .inline}\
then [*c*]{.math .inline} is said to be a cluster point of [*A*]{.math
.inline}.\
 \
It basically means that there are infinitely infinitesimal points
between any point in [*A*]{.math .inline} and the value [*c*]{.math
.inline}.

###### Example

-   The point [4]{.math .inline} of the set [{3,4,5}]{.math .inline} is
    not a cluster point of that set because a 0.1-neighbourhood of 4
    would be the set [*V*~0.1~(4)={4}]{.math .inline}, this set does not
    contain a value [*x* ≠ 4]{.math .inline} that is also inside the
    original set.\

-   The point 6 of [(1,6) = {*x*:1&lt;*x*&lt;6}]{.math .inline} is a
    cluster point of [(1,6)]{.math .inline} because no matter how small
    a neighborhood is made around 6, there will always be values
    [*x* ≠ 6]{.math .inline} inside that interval that are also inside
    [(1,6)]{.math .inline} also observe that in this case
    [6 ∉ (1,6)]{.math .inline}

##### Definition of the Limit \[4.1.4\]

So this is the definition that we moreso use in this unit and the one to
memorise (or the Neighborhoods one seems simpler to memorise).\
 \
Let [*A* ⊆ ℝ]{.math .inline} and let [*c*]{.math .inline} be a cluster
point of [*A*]{.math .inline}.\
 \
Now take some function:\
[\$\$\\begin{aligned} f: A \\rightarrow \\mathbb{R}
\\label{clustlimdeffunc} \\end{aligned}\$\$]{.math .display}\
It is said that [*L*]{.math .inline} is a limit of [*f*]{.math .inline}
at [*c*]{.math .inline} if:\
[\$\$\\begin{aligned} \\forall \\varepsilon &gt; 0, &\\enspace \\exists
\\delta &gt; 0: \\notag \\\\ \\qquad & \\left( x \\in A \\enspace
\\wedge \\enspace 0&lt;\\lvert x-c \\rvert &lt; \\delta \\right)
\\implies \\lvert f\\left( x \\right) - L \\rvert &lt; \\varepsilon
\\tag{4.1.4} \\label{414} \\end{aligned}\$\$]{.math .display}\

###### What’s the Distinction

This is more or less the same as the typical definition given in early
calculus (\[stewartlimdef\]), the distinction here is that we have
specified that [*c*]{.math .inline} must be a cluster point of
[*A*]{.math .inline}, this is more rigorous because c is always such
that there are infinitely many values in any infinitesimal distance
between intself and any [*x* ∈ *A*]{.math .inline},\
So the limit will always mean a continuous approach as we expect, this
is just a more thorough definition.

##### Definition using Neigborhoods \[4.1.6\]

A value [*L*]{.math .inline} is said to be the limit of [*f*]{.math
.inline} as [*x* → *c*]{.math .inline}, denoted
[lim~*x* → *c*~(*f*(*x*))]{.math .inline} if and only if:\

[2em]{}[0pt]{} *For any* given [*ε*]{.math .inline}-neighbourhood of
[*L*]{.math .inline}, [\$\\enspace V\_{\\varepsilon}(L)\$]{.math
.inline}\
*There exists* a [*δ*]{.math .inline}-neighbourhood of [*c*]{.math
.inline}, [\$\\enspace V\_{\\delta}\\left( L \\right)\$]{.math .inline}\

such that:  \

[4em]{}[0pt]{} =0.7cm *If* [*x* ≠ *c*]{.math .inline} is in both
[*A*]{.math .inline} and [*V*~*δ*~(*c*)]{.math .inline}\
=0.5cm *Then* [*f*(*x*)]{.math .inline} must be within the neighbourhood
[*V*~*ε*~(*L*)]{.math .inline}

###### Formally

\
[\$\$\\begin{aligned} \\forall \\varepsilon &gt; 0, & \\enspace \\exists
\\delta &gt; 0: \\notag \\\\ & \\qquad x \\neq c, \\enspace x \\in
A\\cap V\_{\\varepsilon}\\left( L \\right) \\implies f\\left( x \\right)
\\in V\_{\\delta}\\left( c \\right) \\tag{4.1.6}
\\label{416}\\end{aligned}\$\$]{.math .display}\

Defintions (\[416\]) and (\[414\]) are equivalent, and are both
consistent with the initial less rigorous definition
(\[stewartlimdef\]).

##### Only one Limit Value \[4.1.5\]

If [*f* : *A* → ℝ]{.math .inline} and [*c*]{.math .inline} is a cluster
point of [*A*]{.math .inline}, then there is only one value L:
[lim~*x* → *c*~(*f*(*x*)) = *L*]{.math .inline}

### Using Sequences to Define Limits \[ 4.1.8 \]

Now that limits are defined we can use sequences to define them as well,
this will give us more tools to use later and allows a connection to be
made between material of Chapter 3 and 4.

##### Definition

A value [*L*]{.math .inline} is said to be the limit of [*f*]{.math
.inline} as [*x* → *c*]{.math .inline}, denoted
[lim~*x* → *c*~(*f*(*x*))]{.math .inline} if and only if:\

[2em]{}[0pt]{} *For every* sequence [(*x*~*n*~)]{.math .inline} in
[*A*]{.math .inline},\

[4em]{}[0pt]{} *if* [(*x*~*n*~)]{.math .inline} converges to [*c*]{.math
.inline} such that [*x*~*n*~ ≠ *c*]{.math .inline},\

[4em]{}[0pt]{} *Then* [(*f*(*x*~*n*~))]{.math .inline} converges to
[*L*]{.math .inline}

 \
So basically, again, if [*x*]{.math .inline} gets close to [*c*]{.math
.inline}, [*f*(*x*)]{.math .inline} gets close to L, but we took
[*x*]{.math .inline} from a sequence.

### Divergence Criteria \[ 4.1.9 \]

Now we can use the *Divergence Criteria* from \[3.4.5\] to determine
whether or not a limit exists generally or at a point.

##### (a) Limit is not a Specific Value

If [*L* ∈ ℝ]{.math .inline}, then [*f*]{.math .inline} does not have a
limit at [*c*]{.math .inline}, if and only if:\
 \
There is a sequence [(*x*~*n*~)]{.math .inline} in [*A*]{.math .inline}
with [*x*~*n*~ ≠ *c*]{.math .inline}, such that:\
[(*x*~*n*~)]{.math .inline} converges to [*c*]{.math .inline} but the
sequence [*f*(*x*~*n*~)]{.math .inline} does not converge to [*L*]{.math
.inline}

##### (b) No Limit whatsover

If [*L* ∈ ℝ]{.math .inline}, then [*f*]{.math .inline} does not have a
limit at [*c*]{.math .inline}, if and only if:\
 \
There is a sequence [(*x*~*n*~)]{.math .inline} in [*A*]{.math .inline}
with [*x*~*n*~ ≠ *c*]{.math .inline}, such that:\
[(*x*~*n*~)]{.math .inline} converges to [*c*]{.math .inline} but the
sequence [*f*(*x*~*n*~)]{.math .inline} does not converge in [ℝ]{.math
.inline}

##### The Signum Function

The Signum function returns the sign of the input value:

\
[\$\$\\begin{aligned} sgn\\left( x \\right) &:= \\begin{cases} +&1
\\qquad \\text{for} \\enspace \$x \\textgreater \\enspace 0\$ \\\\ &0
\\qquad \\text{for} \\enspace \$x= 0\$ \\\\ -&1 \\qquad \\text{for}
\\enspace \$x \\textless \\enspace 0\$ \\end{cases} \\tag{4.1.10}
\\label{4110} \\\\ &= \\frac{x}{\\lvert x \\rvert}
\\notag\\end{aligned}\$\$]{.math .display}\

Limit Theorems \[4.2\]
----------------------

These are useful for calculating limits of functions, they are mostly
extensions of \[3.2\].

### Bounded Functions

##### Definition

Let [*A* ⊆ ℝ]{.math .inline}, [*f* : *A* → ℝ]{.math .inline} and let
[*c* ∈ ℝ]{.math .inline} be a cluster point of [*A*]{.math .inline}.\
It is said that *f is bounded on a neighbourhood of* [*c*]{.math
.inline} if:\

[2em]{}[0pt]{} there exists a [*δ*]{.math .inline}-neighborhood
[*V*~*δ*~(*c*)]{.math .inline} and some constant value
[*M* &gt; 0]{.math .inline} such that:\

[4em]{}[0pt]{} [|*f*(*x*)|≤*M*]{.math .inline} for every
[*x* ∈ *A* ∩ *V*~*δ*~(*c*)]{.math .inline}

 \
So basically a function is said to be *bounded on a neighbourhood of
[*c*]{.math .inline}* if:

[4em]{}[0pt]{} for some interval (It doesn’t matter how small) around
[*c*]{.math .inline},

[6em]{}[0pt]{} [*f*(*x*)]{.math .inline} can be contained in some
interval

 \

[4em]{}[0pt]{} [\$\\exists \\delta&gt;0, \\enspace \\exists
M&gt;0:\$]{.math .inline}

[6em]{}[0pt]{} [*x* ∈ *V*~*δ*~(*c*) ⟹ |*f*(*x*)|&lt;*M*]{.math .inline}

 \
So for example:

-   [*f*(*x*) = *x*^3^]{.math .inline} is *bounded on every neighborhood
    of every [*x* ∈ ℝ]{.math .inline}* whereas,

-   [\$g\\left( x \\right) = \\sfrac{1}{x}\$]{.math .inline} is ***not**
    bounded on a neighborhood of 0* because [*g*(*x*)]{.math .inline}
    tends to infinity as [*x* → 0]{.math .inline},

    -   [furthermore [*g*(*x*)]{.math .inline} is *bounded on **some but
        notall** neighborhoods of 1*, because an interval around 1 must
        not be drawn large enough to encapsulate 0.]{}

##### Limits imply Bounded Neighbourhoods \[4.2.2 \]

A function is bounded on a neighborhood of a point that is a limit of
that function.\
If a function has a limit at [*c*]{.math .inline}, then [*f*]{.math
.inline} must be *bounded on some neighborhood of [*c*]{.math
.inline}*,\
this flows from the initial definitions because we know that [*c*]{.math
.inline} is a cluster point and that [(*f*(*x*))]{.math .inline} moves
closer to [*L*]{.math .inline},\
hence it must be possible to draw a small enough interval (e.g.
horizontal lines on the [*y*]{.math .inline}-axis) to contain all
[*f*(*x*)]{.math .inline} defined by

### Functions and Arithmetic \[4.2.3\]

Just like with sequences we can define arithmetic operations that relate
to addition and multiplication with functions in order to manipulate
them:\
 \
Let [*A* ⊆ ℝ]{.math .inline} ,\
[\$\$\\begin{aligned} f: A \\rightarrow \\mathbb{R} \\qquad g: A
\\rightarrow \\mathbb{R} \\qquad h: A \\rightarrow \\mathbb{R},
\\enspace h(x) \\neq 0, \\enspace \\forall x \\in A
\\label{seqdefgen}\\end{aligned}\$\$]{.math .display}\

We define the following Operations \[4.2, p. 111\]:

\
[\$\$\\begin{aligned} {1} \\left( f+g \\right) \\left( x \\right) &:=
f\\left( x \\right) + g\\left( x \\right) \\label{addfundef} \\\\
\\left( f-g \\right) \\left( x \\right) &:= f\\left( x \\right) +
g\\left( x \\right) \\label{subfundef} \\\\ \\left( fg \\right) \\left(
x \\right) &:= f\\left( x \\right) \\times g\\left( x \\right)
\\label{multfundef} \\\\ \\left( bf \\right) \\left( x \\right) &:= b
\\times f\\left( x \\right) \\label{confundef} \\\\ \\left( \\frac{f}{h}
\\right)\\left( x \\right) &:= \\frac{f\\left( x \\right)}{h\\left( x
\\right)} \\end{aligned}\$\$]{.math .display}\

###### Limits of Function Operations \[4.2.4\]

Because the limit of a function is essentially the expected value of the
function around that value, it stands to reason that the limit will
distribute over the basic operations:\
[Let the functions be defined as they were in (\[seqdefgen\]) and let
[*c* ∈ ℝ]{.math .inline} be a custer point of [*A*]{.math .inline}.]{}

\
[\$\$\\begin{aligned} \\lim\_{x \\rightarrow c}\\left( f \\right) = L
\\qquad \\lim\_{x \\rightarrow c}\\left( g \\right) = M \\quad
\\lim\_{x\\rightarrow c}\\left( h \\right) = H \\neq 0
\\label{fundeflim}\\end{aligned}\$\$]{.math .display}\

Then the limits are:

\
[\$\$\\begin{aligned} {2} \\lim\_{x\\rightarrow c} \\left( f+g \\right)
&= \\lim\_{x\\rightarrow c}\\left( f \\right) + \\lim\_{x\\rightarrow
c}\\left( g \\right) &= L + M \\label{addlimdef} \\\\\[1em\]
\\lim\_{x\\rightarrow c} \\left( f-g \\right) &= \\lim\_{x\\rightarrow
c} \\left( f \\right) - \\lim\_{x\\rightarrow c} \\left( g \\right) &= x
- y \\label{minlimdef} \\\\\[1em\] \\lim\_{x\\rightarrow c} \\left( c
\\cdot f \\right) &= c \\cdot \\lim\_{x\\rightarrow c} \\left( f
\\right) &= c \\cdot x \\label{conmultlimdef} \\\\\[1em\]
\\lim\_{x\\rightarrow c} \\left( f\\times g \\right) &=
\\lim\_{x\\rightarrow c} \\left( f \\right) \\times
\\lim\_{x\\rightarrow c} \\left( g \\right) &= x \\times y
\\label{multlimdef} \\\\\[1em\] \\lim\_{x\\rightarrow c} \\left( f/h
\\right) &= \\lim\_{x\\rightarrow c} \\left( f \\right) \\div
\\lim\_{x\\rightarrow c} \\left( h \\right) &= \\sfrac{x}{y}
\\label{divlimdef}\\end{aligned}\$\$]{.math .display}\

### Limit Theorems

The rest of the chapter just provides values of varios limits.\
[Let the functions be defined as they were in (\[seqdefgen\]) and let
[*c* ∈ ℝ]{.math .inline} be a custer point of [*A*]{.math .inline}.]{}

##### Limits Captured in Intervals \[4.2.6\]

 \
 \
*if* [*f*(*x*) ∈ \[*a*,*b*\]]{.math .inline} for all [\$x \\in A,
\\enspace x \\neq c\$]{.math .inline}, and [lim~*x* → *c*~(*f*)]{.math
.inline} exists,\

[2em]{}[0pt]{} *then* [*f*(*x*) ∈ \[*a*,*b*\]]{.math .inline}

##### Squeeze Theorem \[4.2.7\]

if \[4.2.6\] is extended to functions, then we have the squeeze
theorem:\
*if* [*g*]{.math .inline} is within an interval defined by the functions
[*f*]{.math .inline} and [*h*]{.math .inline}:

\
[\$\$\\begin{aligned} f\\left( x \\right) \\leq g\\left( x \\right)
\\leq h\\left( x \\right), \\quad \\forall x\\in A, \\enspace x\\neq c
\\label{squeezelimdist}\\end{aligned}\$\$]{.math .display}\

[2em]{}[0pt]{} *then* the limit of g must also be 0

\
[\$\$\\begin{aligned} \\lim\_{x\\rightarrow c}\\left( g \\right)=L
\\label{limisL}\\end{aligned}\$\$]{.math .display}\

##### A Positive Limit implies a neighbourhood with Positive Values

Let [*A* ⊆ ℝ]{.math .inline} and let [*c* ∈ ℝ]{.math .inline} be a
cluster point of [*A*]{.math .inline} as in (3.4.6) above.\
*If*:\
[\$\$\\begin{aligned} \\lim\_{x\\rightarrow c}\\left( f \\right) &gt; 0
\\label{limneighbourpor}\\end{aligned}\$\$]{.math .display}\

*Then:*

[4em]{}[0pt]{} there is a neighborhood [*V*~*δ*~(*c*)]{.math .inline}
such that [\$f\\left( x \\right) &gt;0, \\enspace \\forall x \\in A
\\cap V\_{\\delta}\\left( c \\right)\$]{.math .inline}

 \
This also holds for negative values and basically all it says, in more
rigorous language, is that if the limit point is above the [*x*]{.math
.inline}-axis then there’s gotta be points to the left and right that
are above the [*x*]{.math .inline}-axis as well (because the whole
cluster point thing means everything can be arbitrarily small).\
 \
Although this may start to seem a little pointless, the idea of making
the definitions this rigorous is like writing code in a scripting
language, by using this very precise language, the logical consequences
give us exactly the concept that we want, even though we need to take a
longer or alternate path to get to that concept than we would otherwise
would generally take in order to describe the concept.

Extensions of the Limit Concept \[4.3\]
---------------------------------------

These are written in a particularly convoluted fashion, however if the
preceeding material is understood the textbook can be used more or less
as a reference, hence these notes will be brief.

### One-Sided Limits \[4.3.1\]

##### Definition \[4.3.1\]

Let [*c* ∈ ℝ]{.math .inline} be a cluster point of [\$A\\cap \\left( c,
\\infty \\right) = \\left\\{ x \\in A \\enspace : \\enspace x &gt; c
\\right\\}\$]{.math .inline}\
It is said that [*L*]{.math .inline} is a *Right-hand limit of
[*f*]{.math .inline} at [*c*]{.math .inline}* and it is written:\
[\$\$\\begin{aligned} \\lim\_{x \\rightarrow c\^+} \\left( f \\right) =
L \\tag{4.3.1} \\label{431}\\end{aligned}\$\$]{.math .display}\

This can be extended to left-hand limits as well.

###### Definition in Term of Sequences \[4.3.2\]

As above it is said that [*L*]{.math .inline} is a *Right-hand limit of
[*f*]{.math .inline} at [*c*]{.math .inline}* if:

[2em]{}[0pt]{} Every sequence [(*x*~*n*~)]{.math .inline} in [*A*]{.math
.inline} that converges to [*c*]{.math .inline} is such that
[*f*(*x*~*n*~)]{.math .inline} converges to [*L*]{.math .inline}, given
that [\$x\_n&gt;c, \\enspace \\forall n \\in \\mathbb{N}\$]{.math
.inline}

##### Limit must be equal on both sides

A limit is defined only if the limit is equal from both directions\
[\$\$\\begin{aligned} \\lim\_{x\\rightarrow c}\\left( f \\right) = L
\\iff \\lim\_{x\\rightarrow c\^+}\\left( f \\right) = L =
\\lim\_{x\\rightarrow c }\\left( f \\right) \\tag{3.4.3}
\\label{343}\\end{aligned}\$\$]{.math .display}\

### Infinite Limits \[4.3.5\]

Let [*c* ∈ ℝ]{.math .inline} be a cluster point of [*A*]{.math
.inline},\
It is aid that [*f*]{.math .inline} tends to [∞]{.math .inline} as
[*x* → *c*]{.math .inline}, and it is written:

\
[\$\$\\begin{aligned} \\lim\_{x\\rightarrow c}\\left( f \\right) =
\\infty \\tag{4.3.5} \\label{435}\\end{aligned}\$\$]{.math .display}\

If [∀*α* ∈ ℝ]{.math .inline}, [\$\\enspace \\exists \\delta &gt;
0\$]{.math .inline}:

[6em]{}[0pt]{}
[0 &lt; |*x* − *c*|&lt;*δ* ⟹ *f*(*x*)&gt;*α*,  ∀*x* ∈ *A*]{.math
.inline}

##### One-Sided Limits to Infinity \[4.3.8\]

Let [*c* ∈ ℝ]{.math .inline} be a cluster point of [\$A\\cap \\left( c,
\\infty \\right) = \\left\\{ x \\in A \\enspace : \\enspace x &gt; c
\\right\\}\$]{.math .inline},\
It is aid that [*f*]{.math .inline} tends to [∞]{.math .inline} as
[*x* → *c*^+^]{.math .inline}, and it is written:

\
[\$\$\\begin{aligned} \\lim\_{x\\rightarrow c}\\left( f \\right) =
\\infty \\tag{4.3.8} \\label{438}\\end{aligned}\$\$]{.math .display}\

If [∀*α* ∈ ℝ]{.math .inline}, [\$\\enspace \\exists \\delta &gt;
0\$]{.math .inline}:

[6em]{}[0pt]{}
[0 &lt; *x* − *c* &lt; *δ* ⟹ *f*(*x*)&gt;*α*,  ∀*x* ∈ *A*]{.math
.inline}

##### Ordered Functions

If [*f*(*x*) &lt; *g*(*x*)]{.math .inline}, then:\
[\$\$\\begin{aligned} \\lim\_{x\\rightarrow c}\\left( f \\right) =
\\infty &\\implies \\lim\_{x \\rightarrow c}\\left( g \\right) = \\infty
\\tag{4.3.7 (a)} \\label{437a}\\\\ \\lim\_{x\\rightarrow c}\\left( g
\\right) = -\\infty &\\implies \\lim\_{x \\rightarrow c}\\left( f
\\right) = -\\infty \\tag{4.3.7 (b)}
\\label{437b}\\end{aligned}\$\$]{.math .display}\

### Limits at Infinity \[4.3.10\]

It is also useful to talk about limits as [*x*]{.math .inline} tends to
[∞]{.math .inline}

Let [(*a*,∞) ⊆ *A* ⊆ ℝ]{.math .inline} for some [*ain*ℝ]{.math .inline}\
It is aid that the limit of [*f*]{.math .inline} as [*x* → ∞]{.math
.inline} is [*L*]{.math .inline}, and it is written:\
[\$\$\\begin{aligned} \\lim\_{x\\rightarrow \\infty}\\left( f \\right) =
L \\tag{4.3.10} \\label{4310}\\end{aligned}\$\$]{.math .display}\

If [\$ \\forall \\varepsilon &gt;0, \\enspace \\exists K &gt; 0\$]{.math
.inline}:

[6em]{}[0pt]{} [*x* &gt; *K* ⟹ |*f*(*x*) − *L*|&lt;*ε*]{.math .inline}

###### Limits at Infinity in Terms of Sequences \[4.3.11\]

equivalently to (\[4310\]), the definition can be expressed in terms of
sequences:\

[2em]{}[0pt]{} Every sequence [(*x*~*n*~)]{.math .inline} in
[*A* ∩ (*a*,∞)]{.math .inline} that has [lim(*x*~*n*~)=∞]{.math .inline}
is such that the sequence [(*f*(*x*~*n*~))]{.math .inline} converges to
[*L*]{.math .inline}

##### Infinite Limits at Infinity

So this basically combines \[4.3.10\] with \[4.3.5\]

Let [(*a*,∞) ⊆ *A* ⊆ ℝ]{.math .inline} for some [*a* ∈ ℝ]{.math
.inline}\
 \
It is aid that [*f*]{.math .inline} tends to [∞]{.math .inline} as
[*x* → ∞]{.math .inline}, and it is written:\
[\$\$\\begin{aligned} \\lim\_{x\\rightarrow \\infty}\\left( f \\right) =
\\infty \\tag{4.3.13} \\label{4313}\\end{aligned}\$\$]{.math .display}\

If [\$ \\forall \\varepsilon &gt;0, \\enspace \\exists K &gt;
\\alpha\$]{.math .inline}:

[6em]{}[0pt]{} [*x* &gt; *K* ⟹ *f*(*x*) &gt; *α*]{.math .inline}

###### Infinite Limits at Infinity in Terms of Sequences \[4.3.14\]

equivalently to (\[4313\]), the definition can be expressed in terms of
sequences:\

[2em]{}[0pt]{} Every sequence [(*x*~*n*~)]{.math .inline} in
[*A* ∩ (*a*,∞)]{.math .inline} that has [lim(*x*~*n*~)=∞]{.math .inline}
is such that the limit of the sequence of function values
[lim (*f*(*x*~*n*~)) = ∞]{.math .inline}

###### Ratios of Functions

This result uses (4.3.14) to restate (3.6.5) in terms of functions:\
If [\$g\\left( x \\right) &gt; 0 \\enspace \\forall x &gt; a\$]{.math
.inline} and [*L* ≠ 0]{.math .inline} is defined:

\
[\$\$\\begin{aligned} lim\_{x\\rightarrow \\infty}\\left(
\\frac{f\\left( x \\right)}{g\\left( x \\right)} \\right) \\tag{4.3.15}
\\label{4315}\\end{aligned}\$\$]{.math .display}\

then,

\
[\$\$\\begin{aligned} L &gt; 0 \\implies \\lim\_{x\\rightarrow
\\infty}\\left( f \\right) = \\infty \\iff \\lim\_{x \\rightarrow
\\infty \\left( g \\right) = \\infty} \\tag{4.3.15 (i)} \\label{4315i}
\\\\ L &lt; 0 \\implies \\lim\_{x\\rightarrow \\infty}\\left( f \\right)
= - \\infty \\iff \\lim\_{x \\rightarrow \\infty \\left( g \\right) =
\\infty} \\tag{4.3.15 (ii)} \\label{4315ii}\\end{aligned}\$\$]{.math
.display}\

