\\begin{document} \\chapter{(4) Limits} \\tableofcontents
\\section{Limits of Functions \[4.1\]} Intuitively limits of functions
are the expected value of a function at points that can't be solved
because they are undefined, e.g. \\\\ \\ \\\\ \$\\frac{(x-2)\\left( x+2
\\right)}{\\left( x-2 \\right)}\$ would be undefined at x=2, however as
x is made sufficiently close to 2, that value will become arbitrarily
close to 4. \\subsection{The Limit Generally} From early calculus the
limit of \$f(x)\$, as \$x\$ approaches \$a\$ was said to be some value
L, denoted \$\\lim\_{x \\rightarrow a} \\left( f\\left( x \\right)
\\right) = L\$ \\\\ \\begin{align} \\forall \\varepsilon &gt; 0,
\\enspace, \\exists \\delta: & \\notag \\\\ & \\qquad 0 &lt; \\lvert x-a
\\rvert &lt; \\delta \\implies \\lvert f\\left( x \\right) - L \\rvert
&lt; \\varepsilon \\label{stewartlimdef} \\end{align}
\\paragraph{Remarks on this Definition} Observe that the following
statements are equivalent: \\begin{enumerate} \\item \$x\\neq c
\\enspace \\wedge \\enspace \\lvert x-a \\rvert &lt; \\delta\$ \\item
\$0 &lt; \\lvert x-a \\rvert &lt; \\delta\$ \\item \$\\lvert x-a \\rvert
\\in \\left( 0, \\delta \\right)\$ \\end{enumerate}
\\paragraph{Notation}\\ \\\\ \\ \\\\ If \$L\$ is a limit of \$f\$ at
\$c\$, then it is said that: \\begin{enumerate} \\item \$f\$ converges
to \$L\$ at \$c\$ \\item \$f\\left( x \\right)\$ approaches \$L\$ as
\$x\$ approaches \$c\$ \\subitem This is sometimes expressed with the
symbolism \$f\\left( x \\right) \\rightarrow L\$ as \$x \\rightarrow c\$
\\end{enumerate} \\ \\\\ And the following notation is used
\\begin{enumerate} \\item \$\\lim\_{x \\rightarrow c} \\left( f\\left( x
\\right) \\right) = L\$ \\item \$\\lim\_{x \\rightarrow c} f\$
\\end{enumerate} \\subsection{The Limit Using Cluster Points} In
analysis we more or less use the same definition but we introduce the
concept of cluster points to make it more rigorous.
\\paragraph{Neighborhoods \[2.2.7\]} A neighborhood is an interval about
a value, e.g. the \$\\varepsilon\$-neighborhood of \$a\$ is some set
\$V\_{\\varepsilon}(a)\$: \\begin{align} V\_{\\varepsilon}(a) = \\left(
\\varepsilon-a, \\varepsilon+a \\right) &= \\left\\{ x : \\varepsilon -
a &lt; x &lt; \\varepsilon + a \\right\\} \\\\ &= \\left\\{ x :
-\\varepsilon &lt; x - a &lt; \\varepsilon \\right\\} \\\\ &= \\left\\{
x: \\lvert x-a \\rvert &lt; \\varepsilon \\right\\} \\label{nebhdef}
\\end{align} \\paragraph{Cluster Points} Let \$c\$ be a real number and
let \$A\$ be a subset of the real numbers, \$c\$ may or may not be
contained by \$A\$ it doesn't matter. \\\\ Take some interval around
\$c\$, or rather consider the \$\\varepsilon\$-neighborhood of
\$c\$,\\\\ if, some value (other than \$c\$) can be found inside that
interval/neighborhood that is also inside \$A\$, regardless of how small
that interval is made, Then \$c\$ is said to be a cluster point of
\$A\$.\\\\ \\ \\\\ i.e., if the following is true \\\\ \$\\forall
\\varepsilon &gt; 0, \\enspace \\exists x\\neq c \\in A\\cap
V\_{\\varepsilon}(c)\$ \\\\ then \$c\$ is said to be a cluster point of
\$A\$. \\\\ \\ \\\\ It basically means that there are infinitely
infinitesimal points between any point in \$A\$ and the value \$c\$.
\\subparagraph{Example} \\begin{itemize} \\item The point \$4\$ of the
set \$\\left\\{ 3, 4, 5 \\right\\}\$ is not a cluster point of that set
because a 0.1-neighbourhood of 4 would be the set \$V\_{0.1}(4) =
\\left\\{ 4 \\right\\}\$, this set does not contain a value \$x \\neq
4\$ that is also inside the original set. \\\\ \\item The point 6 of
\$\\left( 1, 6 \\right) = \\left\\{ x : 1 &lt; x &lt; 6 \\right\\}\$ is
a cluster point of \$\\left( 1, 6 \\right)\$ because no matter how small
a neighborhood is made around 6, there will always be values \$x \\neq
6\$ inside that interval that are also inside \$\\left( 1, 6 \\right)\$
\\subitem also observe that in this case \$6 \\notin \\left( 1,6
\\right)\$ \\end{itemize} \\paragraph{Definition of the Limit \[4.1.4\]}
So this is the definition that we moreso use in this unit and the one to
memorise (or the Neighborhoods one seems simpler to memorise). \\\\ \\
\\\\ Let \$A \\subseteq \\mathbb{R}\$ and let \$c\$ be a cluster point
of \$A\$.\\\\ \\ \\\\ Now take some function: \\begin{align} f: A
\\rightarrow \\mathbb{R} \\label{clustlimdeffunc} \\end{align} It is
said that \$L\$ is a limit of \$f\$ at \$c\$ if: \\begin{align} \\forall
\\varepsilon &gt; 0, &\\enspace \\exists \\delta &gt; 0: \\notag \\\\
\\qquad & \\left( x \\in A \\enspace \\wedge \\enspace 0&lt;\\lvert x-c
\\rvert &lt; \\delta \\right) \\implies \\lvert f\\left( x \\right) - L
\\rvert &lt; \\varepsilon \\tag{4.1.4} \\label{414} \\end{align}
\\subparagraph{What's the Distinction} This is more or less the same as
the typical definition given in early calculus (\\ref{stewartlimdef}),
the distinction here is that we have specified that \$c\$ must be a
cluster point of \$A\$, this is more rigorous because c is always such
that there are infinitely many values in any infinitesimal distance
between intself and any \$x \\in A\$,\\\\ So the limit will always mean
a continuous approach as we expect, this is just a more thorough
definition. \\newpage \\paragraph{Definition using Neigborhoods
\[4.1.6\]} A value \$L\$ is said to be the limit of \$f\$ as \$x
\\rightarrow c\$, denoted \$\\lim\_{x \\rightarrow c} \\left( f\\left( x
\\right) \\right)\$ if and only if:\\\\ \\begin{adjustwidth}{2em}{0pt}
\\textit{For any} given \$\\varepsilon\$-neighbourhood of \$L\$,
\$\\enspace V\_{\\varepsilon}(L)\$ \\\\ \\textit{There exists} a
\$\\delta\$-neighbourhood of \$c\$, \$\\enspace V\_{\\delta}\\left( L
\\right)\$ \\\\ \\end{adjustwidth} such that: \\ \\\\
\\begin{adjustwidth}{4em}{0pt} \\hangindent=0.7cm \\textit{If} \$x \\neq
c\$ is in both \$A\$ and \$V\_{\\delta}\\left( c \\right)\$\\\\
\\hangindent=0.5cm \\textit{Then} \$f\\left( x \\right)\$ must be within
the neighbourhood \$V\_{\\varepsilon}\\left( L \\right)\$
\\end{adjustwidth} \\subparagraph{Formally} \\begin{align} \\forall
\\varepsilon &gt; 0, & \\enspace \\exists \\delta &gt; 0: \\notag \\\\ &
\\qquad x \\neq c, \\enspace x \\in A\\cap V\_{\\varepsilon}\\left( L
\\right) \\implies f\\left( x \\right) \\in V\_{\\delta}\\left( c
\\right) \\tag{4.1.6} \\label{416} \\end{align} \\noindent Defintions
(\\ref{416}) and (\\ref{414}) are equivalent, and are both consistent
with the initial less rigorous definition (\\ref{stewartlimdef}).
\\paragraph{Only one Limit Value \[4.1.5\]} If \$f: A \\rightarrow
\\mathbb{R}\$ and \$c\$ is a cluster point of \$A\$, then there is only
one value L: \$\\lim\_{x\\rightarrow c}\\left( f\\left( x \\right)
\\right) = L\$ \\subsection{Using Sequences to Define Limits \[ 4.1.8
\]} Now that limits are defined we can use sequences to define them as
well, this will give us more tools to use later and allows a connection
to be made between material of Chapter 3 and 4. \\paragraph{Definition}
A value \$L\$ is said to be the limit of \$f\$ as \$x \\rightarrow c\$,
denoted \$\\lim\_{x \\rightarrow c} \\left( f\\left( x \\right)
\\right)\$ if and only if:\\\\ \\begin{adjustwidth}{2em}{0pt}
\\textit{For every} sequence \$\\left( x\_{n} \\right)\$ in \$A\$,\\\\
\\end{adjustwidth} \\begin{adjustwidth}{4em}{0pt} \\textit{if} \$\\left(
x\_n \\right)\$ converges to \$c\$ such that \$x\_n \\neq c\$, \\\\
\\end{adjustwidth} \\begin{adjustwidth}{4em}{0pt} \\textit{Then}
\$\\left( f\\left( x\_{n} \\right) \\right)\$ converges to \$L\$
\\end{adjustwidth} \\ \\\\ So basically, again, if \$x\$ gets close to
\$c\$, \$f\\left( x \\right)\$ gets close to L, but we took \$x\$ from a
sequence. \\newpage \\subsection{Divergence Criteria \[ 4.1.9 \]} Now we
can use the \\textit{Divergence Criteria} from \[3.4.5\] to determine
whether or not a limit exists generally or at a point. \\paragraph{(a)
Limit is not a Specific Value} If \$L \\in \\mathbb{R}\$, then \$f\$
does not have a limit at \$c\$, if and only if:\\\\ \\ \\\\ There is a
sequence \$\\left( x\_{n} \\right)\$ in \$A\$ with \$x\_n \\neq c\$,
such that: \\\\ \\hangindent =2cm \$\\left( x\_n \\right)\$ converges to
\$c\$ but the sequence \$f\\left( x\_n \\right)\$ does not converge to
\$L\$ \\paragraph{(b) No Limit whatsover} If \$L \\in \\mathbb{R}\$,
then \$f\$ does not have a limit at \$c\$, if and only if:\\\\ \\ \\\\
There is a sequence \$\\left( x\_{n} \\right)\$ in \$A\$ with \$x\_n
\\neq c\$, such that: \\\\ \\hangindent=3cm \$\\left( x\_n \\right)\$
converges to \$c\$ but the sequence \$f\\left( x\_n \\right)\$ does not
converge in \$\\mathbb{R}\$ \\paragraph{The Signum Function} The Signum
function returns the sign of the input value: \\begin{align} sgn\\left(
x \\right) &:= \\begin{cases} +&1 \\qquad \\text{for} \\enspace \$x
\\textgreater \\enspace 0\$ \\\\ &0 \\qquad \\text{for} \\enspace \$x=
0\$ \\\\ -&1 \\qquad \\text{for} \\enspace \$x \\textless \\enspace 0\$
\\end{cases} \\tag{4.1.10} \\label{4110} \\\\ &= \\frac{x}{\\lvert x
\\rvert} \\notag \\end{align} \\section{Limit Theorems \[4.2\]} These
are useful for calculating limits of functions, they are mostly
extensions of \[3.2\]. \\subsection{Bounded Functions}
\\paragraph{Definition} Let \$A \\subseteq \\mathbb{R}\$, \$f: A
\\rightarrow \\mathbb{R}\$ and let \$c \\in \\mathbb{R}\$ be a cluster
point of \$A\$. \\\\ It is said that \\textit{f is bounded on a
neighbourhood of} \$c\$ if:\\\\ \\begin{adjustwidth}{2em}{0pt} there
exists a \$\\delta\$-neighborhood \$V\_{\\delta}\\left( c \\right)\$ and
some constant value \$M&gt;0\$ such that: \\\\ \\end{adjustwidth}
\\begin{adjustwidth}{4em}{0pt} \$\\lvert f\\left( x \\right) \\rvert
\\leq M\$ for every \$ x \\in A\\cap V\_{\\delta}\\left( c \\right)\$
\\end{adjustwidth} \\ \\\\ So basically a function is said to be
\\textit{bounded on a neighbourhood of \$c\$} if:
\\begin{adjustwidth}{4em}{0pt} for some interval (It doesn't matter how
small) around \$c\$, \\end{adjustwidth} \\begin{adjustwidth}{6em}{0pt}
\$f(x)\$ can be contained in some interval \\end{adjustwidth} \\ \\\\
\\begin{adjustwidth}{4em}{0pt} \$\\exists \\delta&gt;0, \\enspace
\\exists M&gt;0:\$ \\end{adjustwidth} \\begin{adjustwidth}{6em}{0pt} \$x
\\in V\_{\\delta}\\left( c \\right) \\implies \\lvert f\\left( x
\\right) \\rvert &lt; M\$ \\end{adjustwidth} \\ \\\\ So for example:
\\begin{itemize} \\item \$f\\left( x \\right) = x\^{3}\$ is
\\textit{bounded on every neighborhood of every \$x \\in \\mathbb{R}\$ }
whereas, \\item \$g\\left( x \\right) = \\sfrac{1}{x}\$ is
\\textit{\\textbf{not} bounded on a neighborhood of 0} because
\$g\\left( x \\right)\$ tends to infinity as \$x \\rightarrow 0\$,
\\begin{itemize} \\item {\\footnotesize furthermore \$g\\left( x
\\right)\$ is \\textit{bounded on \\textbf{some but notall}
neighborhoods of 1}, because an interval around 1 must not be drawn
large enough to encapsulate 0.} \\end{itemize} \\end{itemize}
\\paragraph{Limits imply Bounded Neighbourhoods \[4.2.2 \]} A function
is bounded on a neighborhood of a point that is a limit of that
function. \\\\ \\noindent If a function has a limit at \$c\$, then \$f\$
must be \\textit{bounded on some neighborhood of \$c\$},\\\\ this flows
from the initial definitions because we know that \$c\$ is a cluster
point and that \$\\left( f\\left( x \\right) \\right)\$ moves closer to
\$L\$, \\\\ hence it must be possible to draw a small enough interval
(e.g. horizontal lines on the \$y\$-axis) to contain all \$f\\left( x
\\right)\$ defined by \\subsection{Functions and Arithmetic \[4.2.3\]}
Just like with sequences we can define arithmetic operations that relate
to addition and multiplication with functions in order to manipulate
them: \\\\ \\ \\\\ Let \$A \\subseteq \\mathbb{R}\$ , \\begin{align} f:
A \\rightarrow \\mathbb{R} \\qquad g: A \\rightarrow \\mathbb{R} \\qquad
h: A \\rightarrow \\mathbb{R}, \\enspace h(x) \\neq 0, \\enspace
\\forall x \\in A \\label{seqdefgen} \\end{align} \\noindent We define
the following Operations \[4.2, p. 111\]: \\begin{alignat}{1} \\left(
f+g \\right) \\left( x \\right) &:= f\\left( x \\right) + g\\left( x
\\right) \\label{addfundef} \\\\ \\left( f-g \\right) \\left( x \\right)
&:= f\\left( x \\right) + g\\left( x \\right) \\label{subfundef} \\\\
\\left( fg \\right) \\left( x \\right) &:= f\\left( x \\right) \\times
g\\left( x \\right) \\label{multfundef} \\\\ \\left( bf \\right) \\left(
x \\right) &:= b \\times f\\left( x \\right) \\label{confundef} \\\\
\\left( \\frac{f}{h} \\right)\\left( x \\right) &:= \\frac{f\\left( x
\\right)}{h\\left( x \\right)} \\end{alignat}
%\\begin{tabular}{&lt;{\$}l&gt;{\$}l&lt;{\$}@{}} %Sequence Addition &
X+Y = \\left( x\_{n} + y\_{n} \\right) \\\\ %Sequence Subtraction & X-Y
= \\left( x\_{n} - y\_{n} \\right) \\\\ %Sequence Constant Mult. & c
\\cdot X = \\left( c\\cdot x\_{n}\\right) \\\\ %Sequence Multiplicaiton
& X\\times Y = \\left( x\_{n} \\times y\_{n} \\right) \\\\ %Sequence
Division & X / Y = \\left( x\_{n} \\div y\_{n} \\right) \\\\
%\\end{tabular} \\subparagraph{Limits of Function Operations \[4.2.4\]}
Because the limit of a function is essentially the expected value of the
function around that value, it stands to reason that the limit will
distribute over the basic operations: \\\\ \\noindent {\\small Let the
functions be defined as they were in (\\ref{seqdefgen}) and let \$c \\in
\\mathbb{R}\$ be a custer point of \$A\$.} \\begin{align} \\lim\_{x
\\rightarrow c}\\left( f \\right) = L \\qquad \\lim\_{x \\rightarrow
c}\\left( g \\right) = M \\quad \\lim\_{x\\rightarrow c}\\left( h
\\right) = H \\neq 0 \\label{fundeflim} \\end{align} Then the limits
are: \\begin{alignat}{2} \\lim\_{x\\rightarrow c} \\left( f+g \\right)
&= \\lim\_{x\\rightarrow c}\\left( f \\right) + \\lim\_{x\\rightarrow
c}\\left( g \\right) &= L + M \\label{addlimdef} \\\\\[1em\]
\\lim\_{x\\rightarrow c} \\left( f-g \\right) &= \\lim\_{x\\rightarrow
c} \\left( f \\right) - \\lim\_{x\\rightarrow c} \\left( g \\right) &= x
- y \\label{minlimdef} \\\\\[1em\] \\lim\_{x\\rightarrow c} \\left( c
\\cdot f \\right) &= c \\cdot \\lim\_{x\\rightarrow c} \\left( f
\\right) &= c \\cdot x \\label{conmultlimdef} \\\\\[1em\]
\\lim\_{x\\rightarrow c} \\left( f\\times g \\right) &=
\\lim\_{x\\rightarrow c} \\left( f \\right) \\times
\\lim\_{x\\rightarrow c} \\left( g \\right) &= x \\times y
\\label{multlimdef} \\\\\[1em\] \\lim\_{x\\rightarrow c} \\left( f/h
\\right) &= \\lim\_{x\\rightarrow c} \\left( f \\right) \\div
\\lim\_{x\\rightarrow c} \\left( h \\right) &= \\sfrac{x}{y}
\\label{divlimdef} \\end{alignat} \\subsection{Limit Theorems} The rest
of the chapter just provides values of varios limits. \\\\ \\noindent
{\\small Let the functions be defined as they were in (\\ref{seqdefgen})
and let \$c\\in \\mathbb{R}\$ be a custer point of \$A\$.}
\\paragraph{Limits Captured in Intervals \[4.2.6\]}\\ \\\\ \\ \\\\
\\textit{if} \$f\\left( x \\right) \\in \\left\[ a,b \\right\]\$ for all
\$x \\in A, \\enspace x \\neq c\$, and \$\\lim\_{x\\rightarrow c}\\left(
f \\right)\$ exists,\\\\ \\begin{adjustwidth}{2em}{0pt} \\textit{then}
\$f\\left( x \\right) \\in \\left\[ a,b \\right\]\$ \\end{adjustwidth}
\\paragraph{Squeeze Theorem \[4.2.7\]} if \[4.2.6\] is extended to
functions, then we have the squeeze theorem:\\\\ \\textit{if} \$g\$ is
within an interval defined by the functions \$f\$ and \$h\$:
\\begin{align} f\\left( x \\right) \\leq g\\left( x \\right) \\leq
h\\left( x \\right), \\quad \\forall x\\in A, \\enspace x\\neq c
\\label{squeezelimdist} \\end{align} \\begin{adjustwidth}{2em}{0pt}
\\textit{then} the limit of g must also be 0 \\end{adjustwidth}
\\begin{align} \\lim\_{x\\rightarrow c}\\left( g \\right)=L
\\label{limisL} \\end{align} \\paragraph{A Positive Limit implies a
neighbourhood with Positive Values} Let \$A \\subseteq \\mathbb{R}\$ and
let \$c \\in \\mathbb{R}\$ be a cluster point of \$A\$ as in (3.4.6)
above. \\\\ \\textit{If}: \\begin{align} \\lim\_{x\\rightarrow c}\\left(
f \\right) &gt; 0 \\label{limneighbourpor} \\end{align} \\textit{Then:}
\\begin{adjustwidth}{4em}{0pt} there is a neighborhood
\$V\_{\\delta}(c)\$ such that \$f\\left( x \\right) &gt;0, \\enspace
\\forall x \\in A \\cap V\_{\\delta}\\left( c \\right)\$
\\end{adjustwidth} \\ \\\\ \\noindent This also holds for negative
values and basically all it says, in more rigorous language, is that if
the limit point is above the \$x\$-axis then there's gotta be points to
the left and right that are above the \$x\$-axis as well (because the
whole cluster point thing means everything can be arbitrarily
small).\\\\ \\ \\\\ Although this may start to seem a little pointless,
the idea of making the definitions this rigorous is like writing code in
a scripting language, by using this very precise language, the logical
consequences give us exactly the concept that we want, even though we
need to take a longer or alternate path to get to that concept than we
would otherwise would generally take in order to describe the concept.
\\section{Extensions of the Limit Concept \[4.3\]} These are written in
a particularly convoluted fashion, however if the preceeding material is
understood the textbook can be used more or less as a reference, hence
these notes will be brief. \\subsection{One-Sided Limits \[4.3.1\]}
\\paragraph{Definition \[4.3.1\]} Let \$c \\in \\mathbb{R}\$ be a
cluster point of \$A\\cap \\left( c, \\infty \\right) = \\left\\{ x \\in
A \\enspace : \\enspace x &gt; c \\right\\}\$ \\\\ It is said that \$L\$
is a \\textit{Right-hand limit of \$f\$ at \$c\$} and it is written:
\\begin{align} \\lim\_{x \\rightarrow c\^+} \\left( f \\right) = L
\\tag{4.3.1} \\label{431} \\end{align} This can be extended to left-hand
limits as well. \\subparagraph{Definition in Term of Sequences
\[4.3.2\]} As above it is said that \$L\$ is a \\textit{Right-hand limit
of \$f\$ at \$c\$} if: \\begin{adjustwidth}{2em}{0pt} Every sequence
\$\\left( x\_n \\right)\$ in \$A\$ that converges to \$c\$ is such that
\$f\\left( x\_n \\right)\$ converges to \$L\$, given that \$x\_n&gt;c,
\\enspace \\forall n \\in \\mathbb{N}\$ \\end{adjustwidth}
\\paragraph{Limit must be equal on both sides} A limit is defined only
if the limit is equal from both directions \\begin{align}
\\lim\_{x\\rightarrow c}\\left( f \\right) = L \\iff
\\lim\_{x\\rightarrow c\^+}\\left( f \\right) = L =
\\lim\_{x\\rightarrow c }\\left( f \\right) \\tag{3.4.3} \\label{343}
\\end{align} \\subsection{Infinite Limits \[4.3.5\]} Let \$c \\in
\\mathbb{R}\$ be a cluster point of \$A\$,\\\\ It is aid that \$f\$
tends to \$\\infty\$ as \$x \\rightarrow c\$, and it is written:
\\begin{align} \\lim\_{x\\rightarrow c}\\left( f \\right) = \\infty
\\tag{4.3.5} \\label{435} \\end{align} If \$\\forall \\alpha \\in
\\mathbb{R}\$, \$\\enspace \\exists \\delta &gt; 0\$:
\\begin{adjustwidth}{6em}{0pt} \$0 &lt; \\lvert x - c \\rvert &lt;
\\delta \\implies f(x)&gt;\\alpha, \\quad \\forall x \\in A\$
\\end{adjustwidth} \\paragraph{One-Sided Limits to Infinity \[4.3.8\]}
Let \$c \\in \\mathbb{R}\$ be a cluster point of \$A\\cap \\left( c,
\\infty \\right) = \\left\\{ x \\in A \\enspace : \\enspace x &gt; c
\\right\\}\$,\\\\ It is aid that \$f\$ tends to \$\\infty\$ as \$x
\\rightarrow c\^+\$, and it is written: \\begin{align}
\\lim\_{x\\rightarrow c}\\left( f \\right) = \\infty \\tag{4.3.8}
\\label{438} \\end{align} If \$\\forall \\alpha \\in \\mathbb{R}\$,
\$\\enspace \\exists \\delta &gt; 0\$: \\begin{adjustwidth}{6em}{0pt}
\$0 &lt; x - c &lt; \\delta \\implies f(x)&gt;\\alpha, \\quad \\forall x
\\in A\$ \\end{adjustwidth} \\paragraph{Ordered Functions} If \$f\\left(
x \\right) &lt; g\\left( x \\right)\$, then: \\begin{align}
\\lim\_{x\\rightarrow c}\\left( f \\right) = \\infty &\\implies
\\lim\_{x \\rightarrow c}\\left( g \\right) = \\infty \\tag{4.3.7 (a)}
\\label{437a}\\\\ \\lim\_{x\\rightarrow c}\\left( g \\right) = -\\infty
&\\implies \\lim\_{x \\rightarrow c}\\left( f \\right) = -\\infty
\\tag{4.3.7 (b)} \\label{437b} \\end{align} \\subsection{Limits at
Infinity \[4.3.10\]} It is also useful to talk about limits as \$x\$
tends to \$\\infty\$ Let \$\\left( a, \\infty \\right) \\subseteq A
\\subseteq \\mathbb{R}\$ for some \$a in \\mathbb{R}\$\\\\ It is aid
that the limit of \$f\$ as \$x \\rightarrow \\infty\$ is \$L\$, and it
is written: \\begin{align} \\lim\_{x\\rightarrow \\infty}\\left( f
\\right) = L \\tag{4.3.10} \\label{4310} \\end{align} If \$ \\forall
\\varepsilon &gt;0, \\enspace \\exists K &gt; 0\$:
\\begin{adjustwidth}{6em}{0pt} \$x &gt; K \\implies \\lvert f\\left( x
\\right) - L \\rvert &lt; \\varepsilon\$ \\end{adjustwidth}
\\subparagraph{Limits at Infinity in Terms of Sequences \[4.3.11\]}
equivalently to (\\ref{4310}), the definition can be expressed in terms
of sequences: \\\\ \\begin{adjustwidth}{2em}{0pt} Every sequence
\$\\left( x\_n \\right)\$ in \$A\\cap \\left( a, \\infty \\right)\$ that
has \$\\lim(x\_n) = \\infty\$ is such that the sequence \$\\left(
f\\left( x\_n \\right) \\right)\$ converges to \$L\$ \\end{adjustwidth}
\\paragraph{Infinite Limits at Infinity} So this basically combines
\[4.3.10\] with \[4.3.5\] Let \$\\left( a, \\infty \\right) \\subseteq A
\\subseteq \\mathbb{R}\$ for some \$a \\in \\mathbb{R}\$\\\\ \\ \\\\ It
is aid that \$f\$ tends to \$\\infty\$ as \$x\\rightarrow \\infty\$, and
it is written: \\begin{align} \\lim\_{x\\rightarrow \\infty}\\left( f
\\right) = \\infty \\tag{4.3.13} \\label{4313} \\end{align} If \$
\\forall \\varepsilon &gt;0, \\enspace \\exists K &gt; \\alpha\$:
\\begin{adjustwidth}{6em}{0pt} \$x &gt; K \\implies f\\left( x \\right)
&gt; \\alpha \$ \\end{adjustwidth} \\subparagraph{Infinite Limits at
Infinity in Terms of Sequences \[4.3.14\]} equivalently to
(\\ref{4313}), the definition can be expressed in terms of sequences:
\\\\ \\begin{adjustwidth}{2em}{0pt} Every sequence \$\\left( x\_n
\\right)\$ in \$A\\cap \\left( a, \\infty \\right)\$ that has
\$\\lim(x\_n) = \\infty\$ is such that the limit of the sequence of
function values \$\\lim\\left( f\\left( x\_n \\right) \\right)=\\infty\$
\\end{adjustwidth} \\subparagraph{Ratios of Functions} This result uses
(4.3.14) to restate (3.6.5) in terms of functions: \\\\ If \$g\\left( x
\\right) &gt; 0 \\enspace \\forall x &gt; a\$ and \$L\\neq 0\$ is
defined: \\begin{align} lim\_{x\\rightarrow \\infty}\\left(
\\frac{f\\left( x \\right)}{g\\left( x \\right)} \\right) \\tag{4.3.15}
\\label{4315} \\end{align} then, \\begin{align} L &gt; 0 \\implies
\\lim\_{x\\rightarrow \\infty}\\left( f \\right) = \\infty \\iff
\\lim\_{x \\rightarrow \\infty \\left( g \\right) = \\infty}
\\tag{4.3.15 (i)} \\label{4315i} \\\\ L &lt; 0 \\implies
\\lim\_{x\\rightarrow \\infty}\\left( f \\right) = - \\infty \\iff
\\lim\_{x \\rightarrow \\infty \\left( g \\right) = \\infty}
\\tag{4.3.15 (ii)} \\label{4315ii} \\end{align} \\end{document}
